const a = [
  {"id":1856,"text":"Caplan syndrome consists of which of the following?","explanation":"Caplan syndrome is a specific clinical entity characterized by the presence of **rheumatoid arthritis (RA) in combination with pneumoconiosis**, particularly coal worker's pneumoconiosis or silicosis. It is important to note that Caplan syndrome is specifically associated with pneumoconiosis and not other forms of interstitial lung disease.\r\n\r\nThe syndrome was first described in coal miners with concomitant RA, but it can also occur in individuals exposed to other dust particles, such as silica. The pathogenesis of Caplan syndrome is not completely understood, but it is believed to involve the interaction between environmental exposures and an underlying genetic predisposition to developing RA.\r\n\r\nClinically, Caplan syndrome presents with characteristic nodular pulmonary opacities on chest radiographs, which are termed \"rheumatoid nodules.\" These nodules are typically found in the upper lobes of the lungs.","reference":"Nemakayala DR, Surmachevska N, Ramphul K. Caplan syndrome. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed May 16, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK499886/","responses":[{"text":"Asbestosis and tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Byssinosis and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumoconiosis  and rheumatoid arthritis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Silicosis and tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Berriliosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7275,"text":"Which of the following is used to determine the pH of the buffer solution?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Strong acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weak and strong acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weak acid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Weak base","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acid and conjugate base","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7283,"text":"What is the term used for the type of hypoxia that includes the disruption of oxygen usage of the cell by the toxic substances, even when there is high oxygen saturation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Pittman RN. Oxygen Transport in Normal and Pathological Situations: Defects and Compensations. Morgan \u0026 Claypool Life Sciences; 2011. Accessed October 10, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK54113/","responses":[{"text":"Circulatory hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemic hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxic hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stagnant hypoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Histotoxic hypoxia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7284,"text":"A doctor checking a chest X-ray notices a rib having the subclavian artery on it. Which of the following ribs has the groove for this artery?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 293.","responses":[{"text":"2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"4","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7301,"text":"Where is the apex of the lung located?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 331.","responses":[{"text":"Below root of neck","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Above 1st rib","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Below clavicle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Below C1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Above 2nd rib","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7312,"text":"Which movement is involved in the increase in vertical diameter of the thorax during inspiration?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 300.","responses":[{"text":"Bucket handle movement","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Downward movement of diaphragm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Downward movement of ribs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upward movement of diaphragm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pump handle movement","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7337,"text":"Which of the following does not characterize the bronchopulmonary segment?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 335-336.","responses":[{"text":"Has its own vein","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pyramidal in shape","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Has its own artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Independent functional unit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Segmental bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7355,"text":"A 4-year-old boy presents to the emergency department with complaints of coughing and wheezing after swallowing 5 rupees coin. The pulmonologist used a bronchoscope to perform foreign body aspiration to remove the coin. What is the most expected place for trapping of the foreign body?","explanation":null,"reference":"Kumar S, Al-Abri R, Sharma A, Al-Kindi H, Mishra P. Management of pediatric tracheo bronchial foreign body aspiration. Oman Med J. 2010;25(4):e019. doi:10.5001/omj.2010.99","responses":[{"text":"Trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right bronchus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lobule of lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchioles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7405,"text":"What is the level of bifurcation of the trachea?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 333-334.","responses":[{"text":"T3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternal angle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T6","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gastroesophageal junction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T4","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7408,"text":"Paralysis of the diaphragm is caused due to injury of?","explanation":null,"reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 304.","responses":[{"text":"Supraclavicular nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sympathetic trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recurrent laryngeal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phrenic nerve","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Esophageal plexus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7470,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for the impairment of oxygen delivery to the tissues?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Carbon monoxide poisoning","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Running a marathon at sea level","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Previous history of cyanide poisoning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doing exercise early in the morning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7492,"text":"What is the type of epithelium found in the vocal cords of the larynx?","explanation":null,"reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 353.","responses":[{"text":"Stratified cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous non-keratinized","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous keratinized","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Columnar ciliated","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7511,"text":"Which one of the following is a term used to describe a lack of sufficient oxygen delivered to the tissues?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anoxia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoxia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7524,"text":"Which of these is not found in the plane of sternal angle?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Pulmonary trunk bifurcation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bifurcation of trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachiocephalic trunk","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch of azygos vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aortic arch","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7536,"text":"Which of these substances is used to synthesize prostaglandins?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Arginine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arachidonic acid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitric oxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glucose","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7558,"text":"Which of the following cells of the lungs secrete surfactant?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Endothelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 2 alveolar epithelial cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Secretory cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous epithelial cells of trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 alveolar epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7616,"text":"Which of the following types of cancer involves the chromosome 3p deletions and mutations in TP53, Rb?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Squamous cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Large cell carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenocarcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Small cell carcinoma","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7628,"text":"Which of the following organisms is most likely to cause pneumonia in an immunocompromised patient?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Staphylococcus aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klebsiella pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mycoplasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Legionella pneumophila","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Haemophilus influenzae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7654,"text":"On examination of histological slides of the lung, students got confused between different bronchioles. Which of the following is the identifying feature that distinguishes respiratory bronchioles from other bronchioles?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"The type of epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The number of cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The presence of glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The interrupted wall of lumen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The diameter of lumen","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7657,"text":"Which of the following enzymes catalyzes the formation of bicarbonate ions from water and carbon dioxide in the blood?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Protein kinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acetylcholinesterase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbonic anhydrase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alkaline phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenylate cyclase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7687,"text":"The pulmonary alveoli are cup-shaped structures and are composed of many cells. Which of the following are the alveolar cells present in alveoli that are cuboidal in shape?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Great alveolar cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Squamous alveolar cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar sac","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Type 1 alveolar cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar atria","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7721,"text":"Gases such as oxygen and carbon dioxide cross the plasma membrane by which of the following methods?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Secondary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitated diffusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Passive diffusion through the lipid bilayer","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary active transport","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Specific gas transport proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7729,"text":"Which of the following features clearly distinguishes bronchioles from bronchi under the light microscope?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"The type of cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The type of glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The presence of cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The presence of smooth muscle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"The absence of glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"The type of epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7733,"text":"What is the most common route carbon dioxide takes to be transported to the cells?","explanation":"The majority of carbon dioxide (CO₂) produced in the body's cells is transported to the lungs for elimination primarily **in the form of bicarbonate ions**.\r\n\r\nAfter being produced as a metabolic byproduct in cells, CO₂ diffuses into red blood cells. Inside the red blood cell, carbon dioxide reacts with water, catalyzed by the enzyme carbonic anhydrase, forming carbonic acid (H₂CO₃). This carbonic acid quickly dissociates into bicarbonate (HCO₃⁻) ions and hydrogen (H⁺) ions. The bicarbonate ions move out of the red blood cell and into the plasma in exchange for chloride ions – a process termed the \"chloride shift.\" In the lungs, the reaction reverses, liberating CO₂ to be exhaled. Approximately 70% of CO₂ is transported this way, making the bicarbonate ion method the most common route of CO₂ transport.","reference":"Hall, John E., and Michael E Hall. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2020: 528.","responses":[{"text":"By dissolving in plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the form of carbaminohemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"In the form of bicarbonate ions","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"In the form of carboxy hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"By binding to plasma proteins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7775,"text":"pH value can be determined by which of the following?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"pH detector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH balancer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH electrode","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH spectrometer","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH meter","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":7827,"text":"Which of the following does not drain into the thoracic duct?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Right intercostal nodes","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Left intercostal nodes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left lower limb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right lower limb","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bronchomediastinal trunk","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7832,"text":"Pleural effusion is checked on X-ray at which of the following levels?","explanation":"Pleural effusion, an accumulation of excess fluid in the pleural cavity, is best identified on an X-ray at the **costophrenic angle**. This angle is where the diaphragm (the primary muscle of respiration) meets the rib cage, specifically at the lateral-most aspect of the ribcage on a frontal chest X-ray.\r\n\r\nOn a normal X-ray, the costophrenic angles appear sharp. However, in the presence of a pleural effusion, these angles become blunted or obscured due to the fluid accumulation. This blunting is often one of the earliest radiographic signs of a pleural effusion. Lateral chest X-rays can also provide additional views of the costophrenic angle and further aid in diagnosis.","reference":"Chest x-ray abnormalities. Accessed May 20, 2023. https://www.radiologymasterclass.co.uk/tutorials/chest/chest_pathology/chest_pathology_page6","responses":[{"text":"Costophrenic angle","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Base of the lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cardiophrenic angle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternal angle","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Infrasternal angle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7861,"text":"Which of the following factors shifts the oxygen dissociation curve to the right?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"High pH","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Strenuous exercise","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Low temperature","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Low concentration of 2,3 DPG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fetal hemoglobin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7887,"text":"Cardiac output is increased during strenuous exercise. How is the increased blood flow accommodated by pulmonary circulation?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 507.","responses":[{"text":"With decrease in pulmonary arterial pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Without large increase in pulmonary arterial pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"With increase in pulmonary arterial pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"With large increase in systemic arterial pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":7950,"text":"Which of the following statements is correct about zone 3 of pulmonary blood flow?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Alveolar capillary pressure remains greater than alveolar air pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It is present in the apices of lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar air pressure remains greater than alveolar capillary pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"It receives intermittent blood flow","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8013,"text":"What is the total compliance of lungs in milliliters?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"1000","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"200","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"600","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"800","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"400","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8787,"text":"Which equation shows that pH of a solution is equal to its pKa when the acid and base are in equal concentrations?","explanation":null,"reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Water dissociation equation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hardy Weinberg equation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Henderson-Hasselbalch equation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Torricelli's theorem","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"pH log equation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":8804,"text":"What is the pressure difference between alveolar pressure and pleural pressure called?","explanation":null,"reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Interpleural pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atmospheric pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interpulmonary pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transpulmonary pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrapleural pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10042,"text":"Which of the following is a prime indication of a high-resolution computed tomography scan?","explanation":"**High-resolution computed tomography (HRCT)** is an imaging technique that provides detailed images of the lung parenchyma. One of its prime indications is in the evaluation and diagnosis of **interstitial lung diseases (ILD)**. HRCT is superior to standard CT scans in visualizing the fine structures of the lungs, allowing for the identification of specific patterns seen in various ILDs, aiding in their differentiation and diagnosis.\r\n\r\nWhile HRCT can also provide valuable information in conditions like empyema, mediastinal abnormalities, pleural diseases, and lung cancer staging, its unique ability to delineate the interstitial changes in the lung parenchyma makes it especially suited for evaluating ILD.\r\n\r\nEmpyema, mediastinal abnormalities, and pleural diseases can be diagnosed using standard CT scans, while lung cancer staging might require a combination of imaging modalities.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Empyema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung cancer staging","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mediastinal abnormality","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial lung disease","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10043,"text":"A young male presents to the outpatient department with complaints of cough and dyspnea. The physician advises a chest X-ray for further evaluation. Which of the following projections is most appropriate for him?","explanation":"The **posteroanterior (PA) view** is the most standard and commonly used projection for chest X-rays. In this projection, the X-ray beam passes from the back (posterior) to the front (anterior) of the body. The PA view minimizes magnification of the heart and provides a clear image of the lungs, heart, and other thoracic structures. It is particularly useful for evaluating lung fields, cardiac silhouette, and mediastinal structures.\r\n\r\nThe **anteroposterior (AP) view** is typically used for bedridden patients or in situations where the PA view cannot be obtained. It tends to magnify the heart's size.\r\n\r\n**Lateral, oblique**, and **apical views** provide additional perspectives, especially if pathology is suspected, but are not the primary views for initial evaluation.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Lateral view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oblique view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteroposterior view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Apical view","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Posteroanterior view","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10052,"text":"A person admitted to the hospital is in a coma. Analysis of arterial blood gave the following values: PCO2 25mm Hg, HCO3- 5mmol/l, and pH 7.1. What is the underlying acid-base disorder?","explanation":"The pH of 7.1 is lower than the normal arterial pH range (7.35-7.45), indicating an acidic condition. The reduced PCO2 (normal range: 35-45 mm Hg) suggests a compensatory respiratory alkalosis, while the markedly decreased HCO3- level (normal range: 22-28 mmol/l) is consistent with a primary metabolic acidosis.\r\n\r\nIn **metabolic acidosis**, there's a reduction in bicarbonate concentration (HCO3-) in the blood. The body compensates for this by hyperventilating to decrease the carbon dioxide (PCO2) concentration. This helps to balance the pH but does not usually bring it completely back to normal. The reduced PCO2 in this case suggests the body is attempting this compensatory response.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mixed disorder","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10053,"text":"The definition of obstructive pattern in pulmonary function tests is best defined by which of the following?","explanation":"In pulmonary function tests, an obstructive pattern is most commonly defined based on the ratio of Forced Expiratory Volume in the first second (FEV1) to Forced Vital Capacity (FVC). In obstructive lung diseases, exhalation is impeded, leading to decreased FEV1, while the FVC may be normal or only slightly reduced. Consequently, the **FEV1/FVC ratio falls below 70-75% of the predicted value** in individuals with an obstructive defect.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"FVC that is less than 95% of predicted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maximal mid expiratory flow is less than 75% of predicted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total lung capacity that is more than 70 to 75% of predicted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Total lung capacity that is less than 70 to 75% of predicted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"FEV1/FVC that is less than 70-75% of the predicted","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10057,"text":"A mother brings her 1-year-old child to the primary healthcare center with complaints of fever and cough and not being able to feed. On examination, the respiratory rate of the child is 55 breaths per minute. There is chest indrawing and wheeze present and the child is lethargic and sleepy. What is the child's classification according to the IMNCI guidelines?","explanation":"The Integrated Management of Neonatal and Childhood Illness (IMNCI) guidelines are used to classify common childhood conditions and guide treatment. For respiratory conditions, these classifications are determined based on symptoms and clinical signs. In the scenario described:\r\n\r\n- The respiratory rate of 55 breaths per minute in a 1-year-old child is above the normal range, indicating rapid breathing.\r\n- Presence of chest indrawing is a severe sign.\r\n- The child also exhibits lethargy and drowsiness, indicative of a systemic manifestation.\r\n\r\nConsidering these signs, the child is classified as having a **very severe disease** according to the IMNCI guidelines. Immediate referral for hospitalization and further management is usually advised in such cases. The classification underscores the gravity of the child's condition and emphasizes the need for urgent, comprehensive care.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Very severe disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Mild pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"No pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough and cold","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10060,"text":"A mother visits a primary healthcare center with her 2-month-old infant. She wants advice on how to prevent acute respiratory tract infections in her baby. Apart from immunization, which of the following is the most applicable preventative measure the doctor can advise her?","explanation":"For a 2-month-old infant, **breastfeeding** stands out as a paramount preventive measure against acute respiratory tract infections (ARTIs). Breast milk is not only a source of essential nutrients but also provides key immunoprotective elements like antibodies, lactoferrin, and lysozyme, which bolster the infant's immune system. These components help protect against a multitude of pathogens, reducing the risk of infections, including ARTIs. Additionally, breastfeeding promotes mother-infant bonding, which has multiple psychosocial benefits.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Better hygiene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breastfeeding","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Immediate care in case of fever","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Better nutrition","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Control of indoor pollution","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10062,"text":"A 35-year-old factory worker comes to the outpatient department with complaints of fever, chills, and pain in the right side of his chest. He has worked in a factory for 8 years. His blood count shows raised white blood cells, normal hemoglobin, and raised ESR. What is the etiology of this condition?","explanation":"The patient's presentation is consistent with lobar pneumonia, characterized by fever, chills, and localized chest pain. \r\n\r\n*S. pneumoniae* is the most common causative agent of community-acquired lobar pneumonia. The symptoms of high fever, chills, and chest pain, along with the mentioned laboratory findings (raised white blood cells and increased ESR), further support the diagnosis of lobar pneumonia caused by this bacterium. Although the occupational history of being a factory worker might suggest exposure to other pathogens or irritants, it does not negate the predominance of *S. pneumoniae* in community-acquired pneumonia cases.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"P. aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E. coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S. aureus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K. pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S. pneumoniae","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10065,"text":"A 47-year-old lady with diabetes comes to the hospital with complaints of fever and chills. The fever is associated with vomiting and cough. She explains she had the flu a week ago. Her total white blood cell count is raised and her culture shows the growth of Factor V and X. What is the causative agent of her symptoms?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms are suggestive of a post-viral bacterial superinfection, which is commonly seen after a viral respiratory illness like the flu. The key clue to the causative agent is provided by the laboratory findings. Growth of an organism that requires both Factor V and Factor X for cultivation is indicative of **Haemophilus influenzae (H influenza)**. This bacterium requires these factors to grow on chocolate agar.\r\n\r\n*H. influenzae* is a common cause of community-acquired pneumonia, especially in patients with predisposing conditions like diabetes. Other options such as *P. aeruginosa* and *K. pneumoniae* are also potential pathogens in pneumonia, but neither requires both Factor V and Factor X for growth.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"H influenza","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"E. Coli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"P. aeruginosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"S. pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"K. pneumoniae","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10069,"text":"A 56-year-old male presents to the emergency room with severe shortness of breath, fever, and cough. The cough is productive with yellowish sputum and has been increasing for the past 2 days. He has been smoking for 25 years. He has been hospitalized twice for shortness of breath. He is taking a bronchodilator preparation twice a day. He denies chest pain or hemoptysis. His temperature is 100 F, pulse 94 beats/min, respiratory rate 25 breaths/minute, and blood pressure is 130/86 mmHg. Pulmonary function testing shows FEV1/FVC ratio to be \u003c70% with no bronchodilator reversibility. FEV1 is \u003c80%. A chest X-ray done 4 months ago shows a hyperinflated lung. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The patient's clinical presentation and findings are consistent with **acute exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD)**. Several features suggest this:\r\n1. A 25-year smoking history is a major risk factor for COPD.\r\n2. Hospitalizations for shortness of breath and use of a bronchodilator suggest underlying obstructive lung disease.\r\n3. Pulmonary function testing reveals an FEV1/FVC ratio of \u003c70% and FEV1 \u003c80%, both indicative of airflow obstruction, characteristic of COPD. The absence of bronchodilator reversibility differentiates COPD from asthma.\r\n4. The chest X-ray from 4 months prior showing hyperinflation is consistent with emphysema, a component of COPD.\r\n\r\nThe presence of fever, increased sputum production, and its purulent nature suggest an infectious etiology, which is a common trigger for acute exacerbations in COPD patients.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Acute exacerbation of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumothorax","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural effusion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary edema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10091,"text":"A 3-year-old boy is brought to the emergency department with a history of swallowing a foreign body. Which of the following is the site of the respiratory passage where it is likely to get stuck?","explanation":"The **Right bronchus** is the most common site for a foreign body to become lodged in the respiratory tract, particularly in children. The anatomy of the right main bronchus plays a role in this predisposition. It is wider and more vertically oriented compared to the left bronchus, allowing foreign objects to pass more easily into it. The left bronchus, on the other hand, is narrower and runs more horizontally. Tertiary bronchioles, alveoli, and upper rings of the trachea are less likely sites for foreign body impaction due to their respective anatomical features. When a child presents with a history suggestive of foreign body aspiration, the right bronchus should be considered as the primary location during diagnostic procedures.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 343.","responses":[{"text":"Right bronchus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tertiary bronchiole","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Left bronchus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Upper rings of trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10109,"text":"Which of the following is the correct stage of maturation of lung development in which the respiratory bronchioles are formed?","explanation":"The **Canalicular period** of lung development, which occurs approximately between 16 to 26 weeks of gestation, is characterized by the formation of respiratory bronchioles, as well as the development of terminal sacs. During this stage, the lung structures become more vascularized, preparing for the potential exchange of gases, even though the fetus still relies on the placenta for oxygenation. The Terminal sac period, from 26 weeks to birth, marks the time when type I and type II alveolar cells develop and the primitive alveoli, or terminal sacs, form. The Pseudoglandular period spans from 5 to 16 weeks and involves the development of the major elements of the lung, except for the structures required for gas exchange. The Alveolar period starts from birth and continues into childhood; this period involves the maturation and increase in the number of alveoli.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 228.","responses":[{"text":"Terminal sac period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Period between 5-16 weeks","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudoglandular period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar period","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Canalicular period","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10118,"text":"What is the amount of air that remains in the lungs after the normal tidal expiration?","explanation":"The **Functional residual capacity (FRC)** represents the volume of air that remains in the lungs after a normal tidal expiration. It is the sum of the expiratory reserve volume (ERV) and the residual volume (RV). After we exhale normally (i.e., tidal expiration), we don't empty our lungs completely. The air that remains, which is not actively exhaled, is the FRC. The vital capacity (VC) represents the maximum amount of air a person can expel from the lungs after a maximum inhalation. Expiratory reserve volume (ERV) is the extra air you can expel after a normal exhalation. Inspiratory residual volume is not a standard term in lung volumes. Residual volume (RV) is the air that remains in the lungs after a forced expiration, preventing the lungs from collapsing.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Expiratory reserve volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Functional residual capacity","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vital capacity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Residual volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inspiratory residual volume","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10221,"text":"There is an overlap between chronic obstructive pulmonary diseases and their etiopathogenesis. Which of the following obstructive pulmonary disease involves the acinus?","explanation":"**Emphysema** is characterized by the enlargement of air spaces and destruction of lung tissue beyond the terminal bronchioles, involving the acinus. The disease predominantly affects the acini, which are functional respiratory units that consist of a terminal bronchiole and the alveoli it supplies. The destruction of the alveolar walls results in loss of surface area for gas exchange and loss of elastic recoil of the lungs. This leads to airflow limitation. In contrast, chronic bronchitis is characterized by chronic productive cough with mucous gland hyperplasia in the bronchi. Bronchiolitis affects the bronchioles with inflammatory obstruction. Asthma is characterized by intermittent bronchoconstriction and inflammation. Bronchiectasis involves permanent dilatation of bronchi and bronchioles due to chronic inflammation and infection. Out of these, only emphysema specifically involves the acinus.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Bronchiolitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10222,"text":"Clinical signs and symptoms of pulmonary embolism mimic myocardial infarction. Which of the following is the most correct method of diagnosing pulmonary embolism?","explanation":"**Pulmonary arteriography** is the gold standard for the diagnosis of pulmonary embolism (PE). It directly visualizes the emboli within the pulmonary arteries. While clinical signs and symptoms of pulmonary embolism can mimic myocardial infarction, it is crucial to differentiate between the two given their distinct treatment approaches. ECG can show nonspecific changes and may sometimes hint towards PE (like the classic but rare S1Q3T3 pattern), but it is not definitive. Chest X-ray is often normal or nonspecific in PE. Radioisotope perfusion pulmonary scintigraphy (or V/Q scan) can suggest PE by showing areas of decreased perfusion with preserved ventilation, but it's not as definitive as arteriography. Venography visualizes the veins, mainly of the lower extremities, and can show deep vein thrombosis but doesn't directly diagnose PE.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Venography","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"ECG","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chest X-ray","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Radioisotope perfusion pulmonary scintigraphy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary arteriography","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10223,"text":"A 75-year-old man is hospitalized for the past week with COVID pneumonia. He develops sudden-onset dyspnea and tachypnea. His lips appear blue and his oxygen saturation drops drastically. Chest X-ray shows bilateral diffuse infiltrates (\"white lung\"). What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"The elderly man's presentation of sudden dyspnea, tachypnea, cyanosis (bluish discoloration of lips), and bilateral diffuse infiltrates on chest X-ray (\"white lung\") following a week-long hospitalization with COVID pneumonia is suggestive of **Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)**. ARDS is characterized by rapid onset of severe hypoxemia and bilateral pulmonary infiltrates, unrelated to cardiac failure. The main histological feature is the presence of hyaline membranes lining the alveoli. ARDS can be precipitated by a variety of direct (e.g., pneumonia) or indirect (e.g., sepsis) lung injuries. While septicemia can lead to ARDS, the presentation here, especially following COVID pneumonia, points more directly to ARDS. Miliary tuberculosis, fat embolism, and acute bronchitis do not fit this clinical picture as well.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Fat embolism","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Miliary tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Septicemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10224,"text":"An 11-year-old child is brought to the clinic with a history of dry cough at night and early in the morning. She complains of her chest feeling tight and a whistling sound when she breathes out. Which of the following is true regarding this patient's condition?","explanation":"The child's presentation of dry cough at night, chest tightness, and a whistling sound on expiration (wheezing) is suggestive of **asthma**. Asthma is characterized by upper airway hyper-responsiveness to various stimuli leading to bronchoconstriction. The major pathologic feature of asthma is reversible airway obstruction due to inflammation and smooth muscle contraction. Over time, with repeated episodes, there can be some remodeling of the airways but not to the extent that they are dilated up to 4 times their normal size. It is also not characterized by chronic necrotizing infections of the bronchial walls. Cough suppressants are not the mainstay of treatment; instead, bronchodilators and anti-inflammatory medications are used. The airway obstruction in asthma is largely reversible, contrary to conditions like chronic bronchitis where it may be irreversible.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Most likely due to upper airway hyper-responsiveness to stimuli","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Airways will be dilated up to 4 times the normal size","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"There is irreversible airway obstruction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough can be treated with cough supressants","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cough is due to chronic necrotizing infection of the bronchial walls","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":10225,"text":"A 30-year-old man suffers a head injury after a car accident. After a few days, he suddenly develops severe hypoxia, dyspnea, and goes into respiratory failure.  What is a lung biopsy likely to show in this patient?","explanation":"The patient's presentation of sudden severe hypoxia, dyspnea, and respiratory failure following a head injury suggests **Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome (ARDS)**. The hallmark histological feature of ARDS is the formation of **hyaline membranes** lining the alveoli. These membranes are composed of fibrin, cellular debris, and edema fluid, leading to impaired gas exchange. ARDS can be precipitated by various direct or indirect lung injuries. In this scenario, the head injury might have led to a systemic inflammatory response causing damage to the alveolar-capillary interface, resulting in ARDS.\r\n\r\n**Epithelioid cells and Langhans giant cells** are seen in granulomas, typical of tuberculosis. **Acute inflammatory cells in the alveoli** denote pneumonia. **Scarring and airway dilatation** refer to bronchiectasis. **Smooth muscle hyperplasia and excess mucous** are features of chronic bronchitis.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Acute inflammatory cells in the alveoli","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth muscle hyperplasia and excess mucous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scarring and airway dilatation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epithelioid cells and Langhans giant cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyaline membranes lining the alveoli","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":10226,"text":"A 30-year-old woman who has a history of rhinitis and nasal polyps presents to the clinic with complaints of repeated asthmatic attacks and urticaria. On further inquiry, she reports taking aspirin for her lower back pain. What is the most likely cause of her asthmatic attacks?","explanation":"The patient's symptoms are consistent with Aspirin-Exacerbated Respiratory Disease (AERD), also known as Samter's triad, which encompasses asthma, nasal polyps, and sensitivity to aspirin and other NSAIDs. In individuals with this condition, aspirin intake can trigger severe asthmatic attacks, rhinitis, and urticaria. The underlying mechanism is thought to involve the shunting of arachidonic acid metabolism away from the cyclooxygenase pathway due to NSAID inhibition. This results in an overproduction of leukotrienes, which are potent bronchoconstrictors and proinflammatory mediators, leading to bronchospasm and inflammation in the respiratory tract. Recognizing this condition is crucial, as avoidance of aspirin and other NSAIDs is the primary preventive strategy for these patients.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"Aspirin causes increased leukotriene production which causes bronchospam","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Polyps in the nose predispose her to polypi in the lungs as well","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aspirin damages her distal airways causing them to dilate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"She most likely has a positive family history for asthma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nasal polyps and rhinitis predispose her to necrotizing bronchial infections","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12078,"text":"Which of the following ribs is characterized as an atypical but true rib?","explanation":"Rib **1** is characterized as an atypical but true rib. True ribs refer to the first seven ribs that attach directly to the sternum through their costal cartilages. Among these, Rib 1 is considered atypical because of its unique shape and features. Unlike the other true ribs, the first rib is shorter, broader, and has a pronounced curvature, making it almost horizontal. It also possesses grooves for the subclavian vessels and a scalene tubercle, distinguishing it from the other ribs.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 293.","responses":[{"text":"12","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12080,"text":"An injury to the phrenic nerve denervates which part of the parietal pleura?","explanation":"The phrenic nerve provides sensory innervation to the mediastinal surface of the parietal pleura. The mediastinal pleura is that portion which lines the mediastinum, the space between the two lungs containing the heart and other thoracic structures. An injury to the phrenic nerve would result in denervation of the mediastinal part of the parietal pleura, potentially affecting sensation from this area. It's important to note that the parietal pleura has other parts, such as costal, diaphragmatic, and cervical, which receive different innervations.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 339.","responses":[{"text":"Lateral diaphragmatic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Costal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cervical","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mediastinal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Apical","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12083,"text":"Which of the following is present in expired air?","explanation":"Expired air contains a combination of air from the anatomical dead space (air that fills the trachea, bronchi, and bronchioles and doesn't participate in gas exchange) and the alveoli (where gas exchange occurs). The anatomical dead space air is the first to be expired, followed by the alveolar air. \r\n\r\n**Dead space air** itself doesn't undergo gas exchange. The **residual volume** is the amount of air left in the lungs after a maximal expiration and doesn't get expired. **Alveolar space air** is rich in carbon dioxide as it has undergone gas exchange, but expired air isn't composed of **only carbon dioxide**; it still contains a large amount of oxygen, though less than inspired air.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 495-497.","responses":[{"text":"Residual volume","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Only carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dead space air","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Dead space and alveolar space air","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar space air","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12084,"text":"Through which of the following anemia leads to hypoxia?","explanation":"Hypoxia refers to a deficiency in the amount of oxygen reaching the tissues. One of the potential causes of hypoxia is anemia. Anemia is characterized by a reduction in the total amount of circulating red blood cells or a decrease in the quality or quantity of hemoglobin. This leads to a decreased oxygen-carrying capacity of the blood. When tissues don't receive an adequate supply of oxygen due to anemia, it can result in hypoxia. \r\n**Hyperventilation** and **hypoventilation** primarily affect the levels of carbon dioxide in the blood, not oxygen directly. **Decreased plasma protein** would not directly cause hypoxia, though it might influence oncotic pressure and fluid balance. **Respiratory decompensation** is a broader term that encompasses several respiratory problems, but it doesn't specifically lead to hypoxia through anemia.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 547.","responses":[{"text":"Inadequate oxygen supply","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory decompensation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hyperventilation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypoventilation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased plasma protein","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12091,"text":"Which of the following cells are not present in the mucosal lining of the nasopharynx?","explanation":"The nasopharynx is lined primarily by a pseudostratified ciliated columnar epithelium with goblet cells. **Ciliated columnar cells** help in moving mucus and trapped particles toward the pharynx, where they can be swallowed or expectorated. **Goblet cells** produce mucus, which helps trap particles and moistens the inhaled air. **Serous cells** are found in the underlying seromucous glands and help in secreting serous fluid. **Diffuse neuroendocrine cells (DNES)** are scattered among the epithelial cells and play a role in various regulatory functions.\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, **Clara cells** are specific to the bronchiolar epithelium of the lungs. They have secretory functions and play roles in detoxifying harmful substances inhaled into the lungs. Hence, Clara cells are not present in the mucosal lining of the nasopharynx.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 350, 352, 357.","responses":[{"text":"Clara cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diffuse neuroendocrine cells (DNES)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ciliated columnar cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Serous cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Goblet cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12092,"text":"The pump handle movement of the rib cage involves which of the following ribs?","explanation":"The respiratory movements of the rib cage facilitate the lungs' expansion and contraction during breathing. These movements involve both the elevation and depression of the ribs. Specifically, the \"pump handle\" movement describes the anterior-posterior increase in the chest diameter. It's akin to lifting the handle of a water pump: when the handle (anterior aspect of the rib) is raised, the other end (posterior aspect) moves more downward than outward. This movement increases the front-to-back diameter of the thoracic cavity, primarily due to the elevation of the sternal ends of the ribs. The ribs involved in the pump handle movement are primarily the upper and mid ribs, specifically **ribs 2 to 6**. These ribs have a more vertical orientation and their lifting has a pronounced effect on the anterior-posterior diameter of the chest.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 300.","responses":[{"text":"1 to 7","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 to 10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2 to 6","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"2 to 10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7 to 12","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12099,"text":"Which of the following is among the factors that obstruct effective communication?","explanation":"**Selective listening** is a barrier to effective communication. It involves hearing only parts of a conversation or focusing on only certain parts and ignoring others. By selectively hearing information, a person can miss crucial details, leading to misunderstandings or misinterpretations. Contrarily, the other options like paraphrasing, active listening, reasonable eye-contact, and selective reflection are techniques that enhance communication. Paraphrasing involves restating the speaker's words in one's own words to ensure understanding. Active listening is a fully engaged form of listening where the listener actively understands, interprets, and evaluates what they hear. Reasonable eye-contact conveys attention and respect to the speaker, while selective reflection is repeating back a part of what was said to confirm understanding.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Respiratory module. Subject: Behavioural sciences.Topic: Communication skills. Sub-topic: Factors that obstruct communication.","responses":[{"text":"Reasonable eye-contact","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Selective listening","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Selective reflection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Active listening","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Paraphrasing","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12107,"text":"Which of the following is most likely to occur in the Haldane effect?","explanation":"**Oxygen replaces carbon dioxide in blood**\r\n\r\nThe **Haldane effect** refers to the phenomenon where the binding of oxygen to hemoglobin promotes the release of carbon dioxide from the blood. Conversely, the unloading of oxygen (or deoxygenation) of hemoglobin enhances its ability to pick up and bind carbon dioxide. This effect facilitates the transport and exchange of gases in the blood. When oxygen binds to hemoglobin in the pulmonary capillaries (where oxygen tension is high), it reduces hemoglobin's affinity for carbon dioxide. As a result, carbon dioxide is released from hemoglobin and exhaled. In peripheral tissues (where oxygen tension is low), the reverse occurs. The unloading of oxygen from hemoglobin enhances the uptake of carbon dioxide, which can then be transported to the lungs for removal.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 529.","responses":[{"text":"Oxygen replaces carbon dioxide in blood","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen replaces water in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen replaces chloride in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen replaces potassium in blood","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Oxygen replaces hydrogen in blood","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12116,"text":"Which of the following best explains the vertical model in the doctor-patient relationship?","explanation":"The **vertical model** in the doctor-patient relationship is characterized by the physician having dominance or control over the decision-making process regarding patient care. In this model, the physician is viewed as the authority, possessing the medical knowledge and expertise, while the patient assumes a more passive role, often just following the doctor's recommendations without much input. The relationship is thus \"vertical\" because it represents a top-down approach. This contrasts with more modern models of patient care where there is a partnership or shared decision-making process between the physician and patient. While the vertical model may have its benefits in certain situations, it has been critiqued for potentially diminishing patient autonomy and not considering the patient's values, preferences, and individual circumstances in healthcare decisions.","reference":"Ahmad W, Krupat E, Asma Y, et al. Attitudes of medical students in Lahore, Pakistan towards the doctor–patient relationship. PeerJ. Published June 30, 2015. Accessed October 15, 2022. https://peerj.com/articles/1050","responses":[{"text":"Patient makes all the decisions on their own","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Patient plays a mutual role in deciding the treatment plan","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctor helps patient find their preferences","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctor only provides facts to the patient","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Doctor taking entire control which is not apparent virtually","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12117,"text":"At what level does the pulmonary trunk bifurcate into pulmonary arteries?","explanation":"The **pulmonary trunk** bifurcates into the right and left pulmonary arteries at the level of the **2nd costal cartilage**, which corresponds to the sternal angle (angle of Louis). This anatomical landmark is significant as it serves as a reference for various thoracic structures. Besides the bifurcation of the pulmonary trunk, the sternal angle also indicates the junction between the manubrium and body of the sternum, the location of the second rib attachment to the sternum, and the level of the T4/T5 intervertebral disc posteriorly.","reference":"(1) Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 336.\r\n\r\n(2) Ball M, Falkson SR, Adigun OO. Anatomy, Angle of Louis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459336/","responses":[{"text":"3rd costal cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st intercostal space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"2nd costal cartilage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"3rd intercostal space","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1st costal cartilage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12118,"text":"Which of the following is best described as the pressure between the lung pleura and the chest pleura?","explanation":"**Pleural pressure** (sometimes referred to as intrapleural pressure) best describes the pressure within the pleural cavity, which is the narrow space between the lung pleura (visceral pleura) and the chest pleura (parietal pleura). Normally, the pleural pressure is slightly negative relative to atmospheric pressure. This negative pressure ensures that the lungs remain expanded against the thoracic wall. Changes in pleural pressure during inspiration and expiration drive the mechanics of breathing. When the diaphragm and other inspiratory muscles contract, the pleural pressure becomes more negative, leading to lung expansion and air inhalation. Conversely, during expiration, the pleural pressure becomes less negative, allowing the lungs to recoil and expel air.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 492.","responses":[{"text":"Intrapulmonary pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Transpulmonary pressure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pleural pressure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intrathoracic pressure","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12119,"text":"At what vertebral level does the thoracic duct enter into the posterior mediastinum?","explanation":"The **thoracic duct** originates from the cisterna chyli in the abdomen and enters the posterior mediastinum at the vertebral level of **T12**. From there, it ascends through the thoracic cavity within the posterior mediastinum. It travels superiorly, passing between the aorta and the azygos vein. As it continues its upward trajectory, it eventually shifts towards the left side and drains into the junction of the left subclavian and internal jugular veins.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 536.","responses":[{"text":"T12","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"L2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"L1","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T10","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12130,"text":"Which of the following best describes the chest placement during a posteroanterior (PA) view of a chest x-ray?","explanation":"In a posteroanterior (PA) view of a chest x-ray, the patient's **face towards detector** is the correct orientation. During this procedure, the patient stands with their chest facing the x-ray detector and their back facing the x-ray source. This arrangement ensures that the x-ray beam travels from the patient's posterior aspect (back) to their anterior aspect (front) before hitting the detector. The PA view is the standard view for chest radiographs as it minimizes the magnification of the heart and provides optimal visualization of thoracic structures. In contrast, the anteroposterior (AP) view, often taken in bed-bound patients, has the x-ray source in front of the patient and the detector behind, leading to an increased heart size and other distortions.","reference":"Broder J. Imaging the chest. Diagnostic Imaging for the Emergency Physician. Published 2011. Accessed October 15, 2022. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8139021/","responses":[{"text":"Supinated against detector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Back towards detector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Face towards detector","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Midclavicular line towards detector","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Midaxillary line towards detector","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12131,"text":"Which of the following structures is not in the vicinity of the transverse plane present at the sternal angle and T4/T5 vertebrae?","explanation":"The transverse plane at the sternal angle, also referred to as the angle of Louis, aligns with the intervertebral disc between T4 and T5 vertebrae. This anatomical landmark is crucial as several important structures are in proximity. The bifurcation of the trachea into right and left main bronchi, as well as the point where the azygous vein drains into the superior vena cava (SVC), occur at this level. Additionally, the right brachiocephalic trunk and the left common carotid artery originate from the aortic arch close to this plane. However, the **Right common carotid artery** originates higher up, branching from the brachiocephalic trunk, and is thus not directly associated with this particular transverse plane.","reference":"Ball M, Falkson SR, Adigun OO. Anatomy, angle of louis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK459336/","responses":[{"text":"Left common carotid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Azygous vein drains into SVC","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right brachiocephalic trunk","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bifurcation of trachea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right common carotid artery","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12132,"text":"Which of the following subset of cells is involved in the pathogenesis of asthma?","explanation":"Asthma is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways, and its pathogenesis involves a complex interplay of immune cells and mediators. Among these, **T-helper 2 (Th2)** cells play a pivotal role. In individuals predisposed to atopic diseases, including asthma, there's a predominant Th2 immune response. Th2 cells release a range of cytokines, including IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13. IL-4 promotes the differentiation of B cells into plasma cells that produce IgE, a key player in allergic reactions. IL-5 is vital for the maturation, recruitment, and survival of eosinophils, cells commonly found in the airways of asthmatic individuals. IL-13, on the other hand, can induce airway hyperresponsiveness, mucus secretion, and IgE production. The cumulative effect of these cytokines and the resulting inflammation and airway remodeling lead to the clinical manifestations of asthma.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural killer cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-helper 2 (Th2) cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-helper 1 (Th1) cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12133,"text":"Tobacco is known to have more than 3900 compounds in it. Which of the following is likely to cause the most damage to the body?","explanation":"Tobacco contains numerous harmful compounds, but **nicotine** stands out due to its addictive nature. While compounds like arsenic, lead, ammonia, and butane in tobacco are undeniably harmful, it's nicotine that primarily keeps smokers addicted to the product. The addictive potential of nicotine makes it difficult for individuals to quit smoking, leading them to prolonged exposure to the multitude of other toxic substances found in tobacco. This prolonged exposure increases the risk of various diseases, notably cancers, cardiovascular diseases, and respiratory conditions. In essence, while many compounds in tobacco can directly damage the body, nicotine indirectly exacerbates this damage by ensuring continued consumption of these","reference":"Dow Lecture slides. Respiratory module. Subject: Community Medicine. Topic: Effect of smoking on community health. Sub-topic: Chemical constituents of tobacco.","responses":[{"text":"Ammonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nicotine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Butane","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arsenic","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lead","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12134,"text":"Which of the following is best defined as a condition in which ventilation decreases and the partial pressure of carbon dioxide increases?","explanation":"**Respiratory acidosis** occurs when there's an accumulation of carbon dioxide (CO₂) in the bloodstream, due to inadequate ventilation. This build-up of CO₂ results in increased partial pressure of carbon dioxide (PaCO₂), which in turn increases the concentration of carbonic acid in the blood, lowering blood pH. The primary reason for this acid-base disturbance is hypoventilation, which might be due to factors like decreased respiratory drive, lung diseases, or obstructions in the airways. The body may respond by increasing bicarbonate ion production in the kidneys to compensate for the increased acidity.","reference":"Patel S, Sharma S. Respiratory acidosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482430/","responses":[{"text":"Compensatory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12135,"text":"A student has exam anxiety and starts hyperventilating. Which of the following will be the most likely outcome in this case?","explanation":"Hyperventilation refers to rapid breathing that exceeds the body's metabolic demand for oxygen. When someone hyperventilates, they exhale carbon dioxide (CO₂) at a rate faster than it is being produced in the body. This leads to a decrease in the partial pressure of CO₂ in the blood, causing a shift in the bicarbonate ion equilibrium and subsequently raising blood pH. This increase in blood pH due to decreased CO₂ levels is termed **respiratory alkalosis**. It's a common response to conditions such as anxiety, fever, or certain medications. When a student experiences exam anxiety and starts hyperventilating, their body will inadvertently \"blow off\" excess CO₂, leading to respiratory alkalosis. The body may later try to compensate by decreasing bicarbonate ion concentrations, but the primary disturbance is respiratory in nature.","reference":"Brinkman JE, Sharma S. Respiratory alkalosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 10, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482117/","responses":[{"text":"Metabolic alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory alkalosis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolic acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Respiratory acidosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Compensatory alkalosis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12136,"text":"What is the term for the 8th to the 16th week of the respiratory system development stage?","explanation":"The development of the respiratory system is characterized by distinct stages that correspond to specific timeframes and developmental events. The **pseudoglandular stage** encompasses the period from the 8th to the 16th week of embryonic development. During this stage, the basic structural framework of the respiratory system begins to form. The conducting portion of the respiratory system, which includes the trachea, main bronchi, and segmental bronchi, is established. Furthermore, by the end of this stage, all major airway branches are formed, though the respiratory portion (responsible for gas exchange) remains undeveloped. It is termed \"pseudoglandular\" because the developing lung resembles exocrine glands in appearance during this stage, but the respiratory units capable of gas exchange, like alveoli, are not yet present.","reference":"Moore, Keith L., T. V. N. Persaud, and Mark G. Torchia. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 10th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier, 2016: 201.","responses":[{"text":"Canalicular stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alveolar stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Embryonic stage","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudoglandular stage","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Terminal sac stage","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12137,"text":"Which of the following is responsible for transporting the greatest amount of oxygen in the blood?","explanation":"Oxygen transport in the blood predominantly occurs by binding to **hemoglobin** present within red blood cells. Each molecule of hemoglobin can bind up to four oxygen molecules, allowing substantial amounts of oxygen to be carried by the blood. While a small fraction of oxygen (about 1.5% to 3%) is dissolved directly in the plasma, this is negligible when compared to the amount bound to hemoglobin (about 97% to 98.5%). Bicarbonate ions are involved in carbon dioxide transport rather than oxygen. Albumin, a major plasma protein, plays a role in maintaining oncotic pressure and transporting various substances, but not oxygen in any significant quantity.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 524.","responses":[{"text":"None of these","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Plasma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicarbonate ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hemoglobin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Albumin","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12138,"text":"Which of the following is the most likely value for barometric pressure at sea level?","explanation":"At sea level, the standard barometric (atmospheric) pressure is 760 mm of Hg. This pressure represents the weight of the column of the atmosphere above a specific point on Earth. As one ascends in altitude, the atmospheric pressure decreases because there's less weight of air pressing down from above. Conversely, pressure increases below sea level, such as in underwater environments.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 511.","responses":[{"text":"76 mm of Hg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"800 mm of Hg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"100 mm of Hg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"120 mm of Hg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"760 mm of Hg","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12139,"text":"At which vertebral level is the thoracic duct most likely to exit the posterior mediastinum?","explanation":"**T5**\r\n\r\nThe thoracic duct, which originates from the cisterna chyli in the abdomen, enters the thorax via the aortic hiatus of the diaphragm. As it ascends within the posterior mediastinum, it is surrounded by the thoracic aorta to its left, the azygos vein to its right, the esophagus anteriorly, and the vertebral bodies posteriorly. Notably, the duct takes a significant course change around the level of the T4, **T5**, or T6 vertebrae. Specifically, it shifts towards the left, moving posteriorly to the esophagus, and then continues its upward path into the superior mediastinum.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 390.","responses":[{"text":"T10","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T5","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"T2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T8","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T12","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12140,"text":"The mediastinal surface of the left lung has a groove for which of the following structures?","explanation":"The mediastinal surface of the left lung features an impression for the **arch of the aorta**. This impression marks the course of the aortic arch as it rises from the heart, arches over the left main bronchus, and then descends as the descending thoracic aorta. The mediastinal surface of the left lung also possesses impressions for other structures, including the heart and the left subclavian artery. However, out of the options provided, the arch of the aorta is the correct structure that leaves a groove on the mediastinal surface of the left lung.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 332, 333.","responses":[{"text":"Ascending aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic duct","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch of azygous vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch of aorta","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior vena cava","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12155,"text":"Which type of epithelium lines the olfactory epithelium?","explanation":"The olfactory epithelium, responsible for the sense of smell, is lined by a specialized type of **pseudostratified columnar epithelium with glandular cells**. This epithelium contains three main cell types: olfactory receptor cells, which detect odors; supporting (sustentacular) cells, which provide structural and metabolic support; and basal cells, which serve as stem cells for the other cell types. Additionally, there are Bowman's glands in the underlying connective tissue. These glands produce mucus, which moistens the epithelial surface and dissolves odorant molecules, allowing them to bind to and stimulate the olfactory receptor cells. This specific epithelial arrangement and the presence of glandular structures differentiate the olfactory epithelium from other regions of the nasal cavity.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 350, 351.","responses":[{"text":"Simple columnar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified columnar with glandular cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple cuboidal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pseudostratified columnar without glandular cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12156,"text":"Which of the following is inhibited by non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs)?","explanation":"Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) act primarily by inhibiting the **cyclooxygenase (COX) pathway**. The COX enzymes, specifically COX-1 and COX-2, are responsible for the conversion of arachidonic acid to prostaglandins and thromboxane. By inhibiting COX enzymes, NSAIDs reduce the synthesis of these pro-inflammatory mediators. This results in the therapeutic effects of pain relief, fever reduction, and anti-inflammatory action. It is worth noting that while prostaglandins and thromboxane A2 are products of the COX pathway, NSAIDs inhibit the enzyme responsible for their production rather than directly inhibiting these compounds. The lipoxygenase pathway, which produces leukotrienes, is not the primary target of NSAIDs, though certain drugs might have some effect on it.","reference":"Karen Whalen, Radhakrishnan R, Field C. Lippincott Illustrated Reviews: Pharmacology. 7th ed. Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins; 2019: 512.","responses":[{"text":"Cyclooxygenase pathway","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostaglandins","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thromboxane A2","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lipooxygenase pathway","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Leukotrienes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12157,"text":"Which of the following is a major cause of cancer, contributing to almost 22% of cancer-related deaths worldwide?","explanation":"**Tobacco** is one of the most significant carcinogens, contributing immensely to cancer incidences and deaths. Globally, it accounts for nearly 22% of cancer-related mortalities. Cigarette smoking is not only linked to lung cancer but also to cancers of the larynx, oral cavity, esophagus, bladder, pancreas, kidney, liver, stomach, cervix, colon, and rectum, as well as to acute myeloid leukemia. Tobacco contains numerous carcinogens, including polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, tobacco-specific nitrosamines, aromatic amines, aldehydes, and various radioactive compounds. Passive or secondhand smoke exposure can also increase the risk of lung cancer and other respiratory conditions. While other factors like radiation, sun exposure, environmental pollutants, and hydrocarbons play a role in carcinogenesis, the pervasive use of tobacco and its profound link to various cancers makes it a dominant cause of cancer-related deaths.","reference":"Anand P, Kunnumakara AB, Sundaram C, et al. Cancer is a preventable disease that requires major lifestyle changes. Pharmaceutical Research. Published September 2008. Accessed October 15, 2022. https://link.springer.com/10.1007/s11095-008-9661-9","responses":[{"text":"Environmental pollutants","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sun exposure","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tobacco","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Radiation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrocarbons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12158,"text":"A 17-year-old man travels to a mountainous area and stays there for years. His body undergoes the process of acclimatization. Which of the following changes is likely to occur in his body?","explanation":"When an individual moves to a high-altitude area, the body undergoes various adaptive changes to cope with the decreased availability of oxygen, a phenomenon known as acclimatization. One of the primary adaptive mechanisms is **increased peripheral vascularization**. This means there's an increase in the number and density of capillaries in the peripheral tissues, facilitating more efficient oxygen delivery to the tissues despite the lower oxygen concentration in the environment.\r\n\r\nOther responses to high altitude include an increase in red blood cell count (polycythemia) to carry more oxygen, an increase in breathing rate to take in more oxygen, and an increased ventilation rate. The body also enhances the ability of tissues to use available oxygen more effectively.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 554.","responses":[{"text":"Decreased use of oxygen by tissues despite low partial pressure of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased ventilation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased red blood cell count","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased breathing rate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Increased peripheral vascularization","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12159,"text":"Which of the following best describes asthma?","explanation":"Asthma is best described as an **atopic disease**. Atopy refers to the genetic predisposition of an individual to produce IgE antibodies in response to common allergens and subsequently develop typical symptoms such as asthma, rhinitis, or eczema. Asthma, in particular, is characterized by chronic inflammation of the airways leading to bronchial hyperresponsiveness and reversible airflow obstruction. \r\n\r\nThe pathogenesis of asthma involves various immune cells, especially T helper 2 (Th2) cells. When exposed to allergens, these Th2 cells produce cytokines like IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13, which contribute to the characteristic features of asthma such as eosinophilic inflammation, mucus production, and bronchoconstriction.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Contagious disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Communicable disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Atopic disease","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Malignant disease","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autoimmune diease","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12160,"text":"The visceral pleura is innervated by which of the following?","explanation":"The pleura is a serous membrane that covers the lungs and lines the inner surface of the chest wall. It's divided into two layers: the parietal pleura and the visceral pleura. \r\n\r\nThe **visceral pleura** covers the surface of the lungs and extends into the fissures between the lobes. It is sensitive only to stretching and is innervated by the **autonomic nervous system**, particularly the vasomotor fibers. This means that the visceral pleura does not elicit pain sensations like the parietal pleura.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the parietal pleura, which lines the inner surface of the thoracic cavity, is sensitive to pain and temperature and is innervated by the phrenic nerve and the intercostal nerves. This distinction is clinically significant, as pain arising from pleural conditions typically originates from the parietal pleura.","reference":"Mahabadi N, Goizueta AA, Bordoni B. Anatomy, thorax, lung pleura and mediastinum. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519048/","responses":[{"text":"Only intercostal nerves","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Somatic nervous system","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Collateral intercostal nerve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Autonomic nervous system (vasomotor)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phrenic nerve","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12161,"text":"Which of the following cells mediate allergic response in atopic asthma?","explanation":"Atopic asthma is a form of asthma that's associated with heightened immune responses to common allergens, especially inhaled allergens. A central feature of the pathogenesis of atopic asthma is the activation of **T helper 2 (Th2) cells**. When these Th2 cells are activated by allergens, they produce a variety of cytokines, including interleukins IL-4, IL-5, and IL-13. \r\n\r\n- IL-4 promotes the differentiation of B cells into plasma cells that produce IgE, an antibody type that's crucial for allergic responses.\r\n  \r\n- IL-5 stimulates the production and activation of eosinophils, which play a significant role in the inflammation and tissue damage observed in asthma.\r\n  \r\n- IL-13, like IL-4, promotes IgE production and also contributes to mucus hypersecretion.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"T helper 1 (Th1) cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T helper 2 (Th2) cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lymphocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Neutrophils","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Monocytes","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12162,"text":"The enzyme phospholipase A2 is involved in which of the following reactions?","explanation":"Phospholipase A2 is an enzyme that specifically cleaves the ester bond at the sn-2 position of phosphoglycerides, releasing a fatty acid and a lysophospholipid. \r\n\r\n**Triacylglycerol (TAG) synthesis** involves the esterification of glycerol with three molecules of fatty acids, which isn't directly mediated by phospholipase A2.\r\n  \r\n**Sphingolipid and sphingomyelin breakdown** are managed by different sets of enzymes, not phospholipase A2.\r\n\r\n**Breakdown of triacylglycerol (TAG)**, or lipolysis, involves lipases that cleave the fatty acids from glycerol backbone in TAGs. Again, phospholipase A2 isn't directly involved in this process.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 207.","responses":[{"text":"Synthesis of triacylglycerol (TAG)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of sphingolipid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of sphingomyelin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of triacylglycerol (TAG)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Breakdown of phosphoglycerides","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12165,"text":"A physician examines an X-ray of the anterior thoracic wall. Which of the following structures constitute this wall?","explanation":"The anterior thoracic wall is demarcated primarily by the sternum, a flat bone situated in the center of the anterior chest. The sternum is subdivided into three parts:\r\n\r\n- **Manubrium**: The superior segment of the sternum. It articulates with the clavicles and the first pair of ribs.\r\n\r\n- **Body of the sternum**: This is the largest part and connects with the manubrium above and the xiphoid process below. It also articulates with the cartilages of the second through the seventh ribs.\r\n\r\n- **Xiphoid process**: The smallest, most inferior segment of the sternum.\r\n\r\nWhile the ribs and intercostal muscles are indeed essential components of the thoracic cage, they surround the thorax and are not exclusively anterior structures. In the context of an X-ray specifically examining the \"anterior thoracic wall,\" the main structures visualized would be the parts of the sternum: the manubrium, body, and xiphoid process.","reference":"Hussain A, Burns B. Anatomy, thorax, wall. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535414/","responses":[{"text":"Intervertebral discs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Manubrium, body of sternum and xiphoid process","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercoastal muscles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thoracic vertebrae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ribs","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12167,"text":"Which of the following nerves innervates the diaphragm?","explanation":"The diaphragm, which is the primary muscle of respiration, is innervated by the **Phrenic nerve**. This nerve originates from the cervical spinal levels C3, C4, and C5. The mnemonic \"C3, 4, 5 keeps the diaphragm alive\" is often used by students to remember the roots of the phrenic nerve.\r\n\r\nThe **Subcoastal** and **Intercostal** nerves provide sensory and motor innervation to the intercostal muscles and overlying skin.\r\nThe **Vagus** nerve is the tenth cranial nerve and has a wide distribution, playing roles in parasympathetic innervation to the heart, lungs, and digestive system.\r\nThe **Iliohypogastric** nerve is a branch of the lumbar plexus, and it provides innervation to some abdominal muscles and the skin of the lower abdomen.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 535.","responses":[{"text":"Phrenic","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliohypogastric","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vagus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Subcoastal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12169,"text":"A resident in the emergency room, while performing pleural effusion drainage, consciously inserts the needle in the 3rd intercostal space just above the inferior rib. This avoids damage to which of the following structures?","explanation":"The intercostal nerves and vessels (including the artery and vein) run along the lower border of each rib. When performing procedures like pleural effusion drainage, it's crucial to insert the needle just above the inferior border of the rib (in this case, in the 3rd intercostal space just above the inferior rib) to avoid inadvertently damaging these structures. \r\n\r\nWhile the **lungs**, **visceral pleura**, **parietal pleura**, and **pericardium** are important structures in the thoracic cavity, the specific technique of inserting the needle just above the inferior rib is particularly aimed at preventing injury to the **intercostal nerve and vessels**. Injuring these structures can lead to bleeding, pain, and potential complications. It's standard practice to avoid the lower border of the rib to prevent such injuries.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 341.","responses":[{"text":"Lungs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral pleura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Parietal pleura","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Intercostal nerve and vessels","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pericardium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12170,"text":"What is the value for barometric pressure at sea level?","explanation":"The barometric (or atmospheric) pressure is a measure of the weight of the atmosphere on a given surface area. At sea level, this pressure is equivalent to the weight of a column of mercury 760 mm high, which is why atmospheric pressure is also sometimes described as 760 mm of Hg. However, 760 mm of Hg is also defined as **1 atmosphere (atm)**, which is a unit of pressure. Therefore, the correct value for barometric pressure at sea level is **1 atm**.","reference":"Sharma S, Hashmi MF. Partial pressure of oxygen. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 12, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK493219/","responses":[{"text":"1 mm of Hg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"1 atm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"70 atm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"76 atm","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"760 atm","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12181,"text":"A benign tumor originating from glandular epithelium is termed as which of the following?","explanation":"Tumors can be classified based on their tissue of origin and whether they're benign or malignant. When considering tumors originating from glandular epithelium:\r\n\r\n- **Adenoma** refers to a benign tumor that arises from glandular epithelium. The term 'adeno-' pertains to glands. Thus, an adenoma is a benign neoplasm of glandular origin or characterized by gland-like structure.\r\n\r\n- **Sarcoma** is a malignant tumor arising from mesenchymal tissues.\r\n- **Papilloma** is a benign tumor of epithelial origin characterized by the growth of finger-like projections.\r\n- **Carcinoma** is a malignant tumor arising from epithelial cells.\r\n- **Krukenberg tumor** specifically refers to a metastatic mucin-secreting tumor of the ovary, usually originating from a primary site in the stomach.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 266.","responses":[{"text":"Papilloma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sarcoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Krukenberg tumor","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Adenoma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Carcinoma","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12182,"text":"Which of the following actions of the respiratory system leads to the development of respiratory alkalosis?","explanation":"Respiratory alkalosis is a condition characterized by a rise in blood pH due to decreased levels of carbon dioxide (CO2) in the blood. The primary determinant of blood pH in the respiratory context is the partial pressure of CO2. When there's a decrease in blood CO2 levels, this leads to a reduction in the concentration of carbonic acid and, subsequently, hydrogen ions (H+), making the blood more alkaline. \r\n\r\nThe action of the respiratory system that can lead to this condition is hyperventilation, where there is rapid breathing leading to excessive expulsion of CO2. Therefore, the action that leads to the development of respiratory alkalosis is the removal of an **excess amount of carbon dioxide** from the blood.","reference":"Brinkman JE, Sharma S. Respiratory alkalosis. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482117/","responses":[{"text":"Remove excess amount of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retain excess amount of hydrogen ions","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Remove excess amount of carbon dioxide","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Retain excess amount of oxygen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retain excess amount of carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12183,"text":"A patient is admitted to the hospital with severe pleuritis. The amount of proteins in the pleural fluid is likely to be more than which of the following in this case?","explanation":"Pleuritis, or inflammation of the pleura, often results in exudative pleural effusions. Exudative effusions are typically characterized by their high protein content. An exudate in the pleural space is identified by a protein content greater than **30 g/L**. This is further supported by the presence of inflammatory cells in the effusion, which aligns with the inflammatory nature of pleuritis. In the context of severe pleuritis, the protein content in the pleural fluid is expected to exceed **30 g/L** to qualify as an exudative effusion.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Perkins JA, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 544.","responses":[{"text":"3 g/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 g/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"10 g/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"20 g/L","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30 g/L","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12184,"text":"The contraction of which of the following muscles is not involved in inspiration?","explanation":"During the process of inspiration, most muscles assist in expanding the thoracic cavity to allow for lung inflation. The **external intercostal** muscles, when contracted, elevate the ribs and thus increase the anteroposterior diameter of the thorax. The **sternocleidomastoid** and **scalenus anterior** muscles help in elevating the sternum and the first couple of ribs, respectively, further aiding in thoracic expansion. The **serratus anterior** stabilizes the rib cage and assists with lifting the ribs during forced inspiration.\r\n\r\nIn contrast, the **internal intercostal** muscles are primarily involved in expiration. They depress the ribs, reducing the thoracic volume and assisting in forced expiration. Therefore, the contraction of the internal intercostal muscles is not involved in inspiration but rather in expiration.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 491.","responses":[{"text":"Scalenus anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"External intercostal","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sternocleidomastoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Internal intercostal","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Serratus anterior","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12185,"text":"A 65-year-old female is admitted to the ICU. She develops chest pain 3 days later. A  chest X-ray is performed and reveals diffuse lung infiltrates. What is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"In a hospital or ICU setting, when a patient develops respiratory symptoms like chest pain and diffuse lung infiltrates on chest X-ray after admission, the diagnosis most strongly suggested is **Nosocomial pneumonia**. Nosocomial refers to hospital-acquired. This type of pneumonia occurs 48 hours or more after admission, indicating that it was not present at the time of admission.\r\n\r\n**Lung abscess** typically presents as a localized collection of pus. **Community acquired pneumonia** would manifest symptoms at the time of, or shortly after, admission, not days later. **Granulomatous disease of the lung** and **Interstitial disease of the lung** have more chronic presentations and are not as acutely related to hospital stays as nosocomial pneumonia.","reference":"(1) Cunha BA. Nosocomial pneumonia. Medical Clinics of North America. Published January 2001. Accessed October 15, 2022. https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0025712505703059\r\n\r\n(2) Shebl E, Gulick PG. Nosocomial pneumonia. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK535441/","responses":[{"text":"Interstitial disease of lung","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Community acquired pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nosocomial pneumonia","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Lung abscess","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulomatous disease of lung","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12186,"text":"A student is studying the contents of the superior mediastinum. Which of the following structures is not present in the mentioned region?","explanation":"The superior mediastinum contains several important vascular and non-vascular structures. Among the options given:\r\n\r\n1. The **arch of azygos vein** drains into the superior vena cava.\r\n2. The **arch of aorta** begins and ends in the superior mediastinum.\r\n3. The **brachiocephalic veins** are formed by the union of the internal jugular and subclavian veins. \r\n4. The **left common carotid artery** originates directly from the arch of the aorta.\r\n\r\nHowever, the **right common carotid artery** does not originate from the arch of the aorta in the superior mediastinum. Instead, it arises from the brachiocephalic trunk, which itself originates from the aorta, but outside the superior mediastinum.","reference":"Stoddard N, Heil JR, Lowery DR. Anatomy, thorax, mediastinum. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed October 13, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539819/","responses":[{"text":"Left common carotid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch of azygous vein","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Right common carotid","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Arch of aorta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Brachiocephalic veins","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12187,"text":"A 60-year-old female presents with complaints of difficulty in breathing particularly in the morning and during changes in position. She is coughing up a copious amount of mucus. Which of the following conditions is the most likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"The clinical presentation of a 60-year-old female with difficulty in breathing especially in the mornings and during positional changes, and coughing up mucus, aligns with the classic symptoms of **Asthma**. Asthma is a chronic inflammatory disorder of the airways leading to recurrent episodes described by wheezing, breathlessness, chest tightness, and particularly coughing at night or early in the morning. The mucus expectorated during coughing can contain characteristic Curschmann spirals and Charcot-Leyden crystals, as a result of the inflammation and cellular composition in asthmatic airways.\r\n\r\n**Pneumonia** and **Emphysema** don't typically present with these episodic symptoms. **Bronchiectasis** and **Chronic bronchitis** can produce mucus, but the combination of positional and morning-predominant symptoms is distinctive for **Asthma**.","reference":"(1) Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Perkins JA, eds. Robbins Basic Pathology. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2018: 503.\r\n\r\n(2) Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 91.","responses":[{"text":"Asthma","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bronchiectasis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12188,"text":"A hospitalized patient suffers from respiratory distress and difficulty breathing. Chest x-ray reveals a white lung. Which of the following is the likely diagnosis in this case?","explanation":"A \"white lung\" appearance on a chest x-ray, combined with respiratory distress, is characteristic of **Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)**. ARDS is a serious condition marked by widespread inflammation of the pulmonary capillaries, leading to increased permeability, alveolar edema, and hypoxemia.\r\n\r\n**Emphysema** primarily causes lung hyperinflation and doesn't produce a \"white lung\" appearance. **Pulmonary tuberculosis** often presents with upper lobe infiltrates and cavitation. **Pneumonia** may cause localized consolidation on x-ray, but it doesn't give a bilateral \"white lung\" appearance typical of ARDS. **Chronic bronchitis** primarily leads to bronchial wall thickening without the diffuse opacification of ARDS.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 94.","responses":[{"text":"Acute respiratory distress syndrome (ARDS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Emphysema","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pneumonia","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pulmonary tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chronic bronchitis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12189,"text":"Which of the following cells is present in the intra-alveolar septa besides pneumocytes?","explanation":"The **intra-alveolar septa** contain primarily two types of pneumocytes: Type I and Type II. However, besides pneumocytes, the intra-alveolar septa also house **dust cells**, which are essentially alveolar macrophages. These cells play a pivotal role in phagocytosing any inhaled particulate matter, including dust, thus justifying their name. \r\n\r\n**Receptor cells** are sensory cells, not found in the lungs. **Columnar cells** typically line various surfaces of the body but are not specific to the intra-alveolar septa. **Sustentacular cells** are supportive cells, mainly observed in the olfactory epithelium, aiding the olfactory receptor neurons. **Basal cells** serve as stem cells in various epithelia but are not part of the intra-alveolar septa.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 14th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2015: 364.","responses":[{"text":"Dust cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Sustentacular cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Receptor cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Basal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Columnar cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":12190,"text":"Which of the following enzymes causes the breakdown of phosphoglyceride?","explanation":"The breakdown of phosphoglycerides is primarily catalyzed by an enzyme known as **phospholipase**. Phospholipases are a group of enzymes that play a crucial role in lipid metabolism. They hydrolyze the ester bonds in the phosphoglycerides, leading to the release of fatty acids and other components. This process is essential in various physiological processes, such as cell membrane maintenance, lipid digestion, and the generation of signaling molecules like inositol trisphosphate (IP3) and diacylglycerol (DAG). Phospholipases can be classified into different types, including phospholipase A, phospholipase B, phospholipase C, and phospholipase D, based on their specific actions on the phospholipid molecule.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 207.","responses":[{"text":"Lipofructokinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sphingomyelinase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phosphatase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phospholipase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Transferase","correct":false,"visible":false}]}
]

export default a